    "descripcionEn": "Neonatal jaundice is a yellowish discoloration of the skin and sclerae of the newborn caused by the accumulation of unconjugated bilirubin in the blood. It is one of the most common conditions in the neonatal period, affecting approximately 60% of full-term newborns and 80% of preterm infants during the first week of life. In most cases, it is a benign physiological jaundice that resolves spontaneously, but untreated elevated bilirubin levels can lead to acute bilirubin encephalopathy or kernicterus, a form of permanent brain damage affecting the basal ganglia and brainstem nuclei. Severe hyperbilirubinemia constitutes a neonatal emergency requiring immediate intervention to prevent irreversible neurological sequelae.",
