    "descripcionEn": "Perinatal asphyxia is a condition characterized by interruption of fetal-neonatal gas exchange around the time of birth, resulting in progressive hypoxemia, hypercapnia, and metabolic acidosis. When the hypoxic-ischemic insult affects the brain, it is termed hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy (HIE), the most feared consequence of perinatal asphyxia. Perinatal asphyxia occurs in approximately 1-6 per 1000 live-born term infants in developed countries, with significantly higher rates in developing countries. Moderate to severe HIE is associated with mortality of 15-25% and long-term neurological sequelae (cerebral palsy, intellectual disability, epilepsy) in 25-30% of survivors. Early diagnosis and treatment, especially therapeutic hypothermia, are crucial for improving outcomes.",
