    "diagnosticoEn": "Diagnosis of perinatal asphyxia is based on multiple criteria: arterial umbilical cord blood gas showing significant metabolic acidosis (pH less than 7.0, base deficit greater than 12 mmol/L), persistently low Apgar score (less than 5 at 10 minutes), evidence of early neonatal neurological dysfunction (assessed using the Sarnat classification for HIE: mild, moderate, or severe), and evidence of multiorgan dysfunction. Complementary studies include continuous EEG or amplitude-integrated EEG (aEEG) to detect seizure activity and assess background pattern, brain MRI (optimal between 3-7 days of life to evaluate the extent of injury), serial transfontanellar ultrasound, and serum biomarkers of brain injury. Monitoring of renal, hepatic, cardiac, and hematological function is essential.",
    "tratamientoEs": "La hipotermia terapeutica (enfriamiento corporal total a 33.5 grados o enfriamiento cefalico selectivo) es el tratamiento estandar para la EHI moderada a severa en recien nacidos a termino o cercanos al termino (mayor de 36 semanas). Debe iniciarse dentro de las primeras 6 horas de vida y mantenerse durante 72 horas, seguida de un recalentamiento gradual (0.5 grados por hora). La hipotermia terapeutica reduce la mortalidad y la discapacidad neurolgica severa. El manejo incluye soporte ventilatorio optimizado, mantenimiento de la perfusion cerebral con presion arterial media adecuada, control de convulsiones con fenobarbital como primera linea (dosis de carga 20 mg/kg), manejo de fluidos restringido por riesgo de edema cerebral, correccion de alteraciones metabolicas y hematologicas, y soporte de la funcion multiorganica. Se evitan la hipertermia y la hiperoxia por su potencial neurotxico.",
    "tratamientoEn": "Therapeutic hypothermia (whole-body cooling to 33.5 degrees or selective head cooling) is the standard treatment for moderate to severe HIE in term or near-term newborns (greater than 36 weeks). It must be initiated within the first 6 hours of life and maintained for 72 hours, followed by gradual rewarming (0.5 degrees per hour). Therapeutic hypothermia reduces mortality and severe neurological disability. Management includes optimized ventilatory support, maintenance of cerebral perfusion with adequate mean arterial pressure, seizure control with phenobarbital as first line (loading dose 20 mg/kg), fluid management restricted due to risk of cerebral edema, correction of metabolic and hematological abnormalities, and support of multiorgan function. Hyperthermia and hyperoxia are avoided due to their neurotoxic potential.",
